---
title: A Surprisingly Simple Roasted Duck with Spiced Lentils and Caramelised Apples
description: When we first started HelloFresh, we used to get all sorts of emails from people saying that they were ‘scared’ of fish. Whether Steven Spielberg related, or something to do with it welding to their frying pan, we soon knocked their phobia into touch with a few easy recipes. Next on our scary-food hit-list is duck, far more simple than you might believe! Our tip here is to leave the duck out of the fridge for 30 mins before you cook it, so it cooks evenly.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/a-surprisingly-simple-roasted-duck-with-spiced-lentils-952b77b3.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/a-surprisingly-simple-roasted-du-d2dd3843.pdf
time required: 30 minutes
cuisine: French
nutrition:
  calories: 436 kcal
  fat: 11 g
  saturated fat: 2 g
  carbohydrates: 45 g
  protein: 40 g
  sodium: 4 g
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/a-surprisingly-simple-roasted-duck-with-spiced-lentils-33-576a944331c0a295068b4568
course: main course
---

Finely chop the @red chilli{1}. Peel and very, very finely chop the @carrot{1}(peeled) (into ½cm cubes if your skills allow!). Peel and core the @apple{1} before chopping into 1cm cubes. Peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}. Cut the @spring greens{1/2}(sliced) leaves into roughly 1cm slices, discard the tough root.

Melt a knob of @butter{1%knob}(if you have some) in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Toss in your apple, a sprinkle of @sugar{pinch}(if you have it) and a splash of @water{1%tbsp} and place a #lid{} on the pan. Allow to cook for ~{10%minutes} until your apple has softened. Remove the lid to thicken the caramelised apple in the last few mins. When the ~{10%minutes} are up, take the #pan{} off the heat.

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees and season the @duck breasts{2} with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cut three slices across the duck skin with a sharp #knife{} and lay in a cold #griddle pan{} skin-side down (just use a #frying pan{} if you don't have a griddle pan). Cook on medium-low heat for about ~{7%minutes} or until the fat is crisp and golden. Transfer to a #baking tray{} skin-side up and cook in your oven for ~{7%minutes} on the top shelf.

> We like our duck pink, if you like it well done, cook it for 15 mins in the oven, if you like it rare, cook it for 5 mins in the oven.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{1%splash} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Gently fry your chilli, carrot and shallot for ~{5%minutes}. Drain and thoroughly rinse the @green lentils{1%can} before adding to the pan, together with the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and the @water{75%ml}.

After ~{3%minutes}, take this pan off the heat. Cover with a lid and leave until it's time to serve.

Once your duck is cooked, remove from your oven and leave it to rest for ~{3%minutes}.

> Leaving meat to rest on a warm plate, allows the juices to redistribute throughout the meat, making every mouthful nice and juicy.

Pour any excess fat from your duck into another frying pan and place on high heat. Once hot, add your spring greens along with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @pepper{pinch}. Fry for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{3%sprigs} then stir it through your lentils. Serve your duck on top of your lentils with a healthy dollop of your caramelised apples. Serve with your greens and savour!